{"type":"message","id":"4a1b4f4f","parentId":"49db096b","timestamp":"2026-05-08T17:04:38.558Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to handle items 2, 3, 4, 5. These are more complex - they involve automation logic. Let me think:\n\n- Item 2 (Auto-Summary Reset every 10 sentences): This needs either a cron job or a session-level mechanism. In OpenClaw, this could be handled by setting up a periodic check or a session hook. But given the complexity, I'll need to create a mechanism that counts messages and triggers a summary+reset.\n\nActually, thinking about this more practically:\n- OpenClaw's compaction handles the automatic context management\n- The \"every 10 sentences\" trigger is something I'd need to track in the session\n- For the summary+reset, I could use a session-level cron or event system\n\nLet me create a practical implementation for items 2-5. Since I don't have direct access to create complex session hooks, I'll create a cron-based approach and a helper script.\n\nActually, for items 2, 3, 4, 5 - these are more application-level concerns. I should create helper scripts that can be called, and potentially set up cron jobs.\n\nLet me think about what's feasible:\n1. ✅ Done - keepRecentTokens=8000, reserveTokens=4000\n2. Auto-Summary Reset every 10 messages: This needs session-level tracking. I could create a counter file and check it on each message, but that would require modifying OpenClaw's behavior which I can't do directly.\n3. External Storage for files >2000 tokens: This is a behavioral rule I can document and follow manually\n4. Kill-Switch at 200K tokens/hour: This could be a cron job that monitors usage\n5. Anti-Loop at 3 repetitions: This needs session-level tracking\n\nFor items 2, 4, 5 - these are complex to implement without modifying OpenClaw core. Let me create practical helper scripts and document the rules, then set up what's feasible.\n\nActually, let me re-read the request. The user wants a complete \"Token Firewall\" system. \n\nI should create practical scripts that implement what can be implemented:\n1. A cron job that checks token usage and alerts\n2. A session tracking mechanism\n\nBut wait - OpenClaw already has built-in compaction and token management. The settings I applied (keepRecentTokens=8000, reserveTokens=4000) will handle the basic memory management.\n\nFor items 2-5, I can:\n- Create a helper script for item 2 (manual trigger for summary)\n- Create a monitoring cron for item 4\n- Create tracking for item 5\n\nLet me create what I can and explain what's already handled by the compaction settings.\n","thinkingSignature":"4d0940d62e355af590aac42237067abd99e9dc610a38b93566bcce8461688fb1"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nItems 1 ✅ ทำเสร็จแล้ว ตอนนี้จัดการ items 2-5 ครับ:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_us8vs8w7xhuh_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p ~/.openclaw/workspace/token-firewall"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":204,"output":630,"cacheRead":42432,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":43266,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778259857434,"responseId":"064d4a9233eb46c6aa951eeb7e7dd9ee"}}
